nodes.text: Absolutely NO increase in price for anything that's already been paid for!
keithanywhere(455): Absolutely NO increase in price for anything that's already been paid for!
Annot: Absolutely NO increase in price for anything that's already been paid for!
There are too many simpleminded examples of why this is just wrong.
keithanywhere(455): There are too many simpleminded examples of why this is just wrong.
Annot: There are too many simpleminded examples of why this is just wrong.
I couldn't even list them all here.
keithanywhere(455): I couldn't even list them all here.
Annot: I couldn't even list them all here.
Bottom line is, once a customer has agreed upon a price with the seller... and that happens when the customer pays... the seller absolutely cannot go back and play "changes" with the price.

keithanywhere(455): Bottom line is, once a customer has agreed upon a price with the seller... and that happens when the customer pays... the seller absolutely cannot go back and play "changes" with the price.
Annot: Bottom line is, once a customer has agreed upon a price with the seller... and that happens when the customer pays... the seller absolutely cannot go back and play "changes" with the price.
Once you pay for it, it's paid for, done...
keithanywhere(455): Once you pay for it, it's paid for, done...

no more money can be collected from the customer.
keithanywhere(455): no more money can be collected from the customer.

Even if the travel provider made a mistake on the price... they should have to absorb their mistake.
keithanywhere(455): Even if the travel provider made a mistake on the price... they should have to absorb their mistake.

It's the travel provider's mistake...
keithanywhere(455): It's the travel provider's mistake...
Annot: It's the travel provider's mistake...
the customer agreed to the deal in good faith with the seller and paid the seller as expected.

Annot: the customer agreed to the deal in good faith with the seller and paid the seller as expected.
There is no way the seller should be permitted to collect additional funds from the customer.
keithanywhere(455): There is no way the seller should be permitted to collect additional funds from the customer.
Annot: There is no way the seller should be permitted to collect additional funds from the customer.
I definitely agree with Keithanywhere's statement that "Once you pay for it, it's paid for, done... no more money can be collected from the customer."
brianne(460): I definitely agree with Keithanywhere's statement that "Once you pay for it, it's paid for, done... no more money can be collected from the customer."
Annot: I definitely agree with Keithanywhere's statement that "Once you pay for it, it's paid for, done... no more money can be collected from the customer."
I can't think of any other business transaction where it would be acceptable for a company to require a customer to pay more money after the transaction is completed.
brianne(460): I can't think of any other business transaction where it would be acceptable for a company to require a customer to pay more money after the transaction is completed.
Annot: I can't think of any other business transaction where it would be acceptable for a company to require a customer to pay more money after the transaction is completed.
In an extreme situation like the one you proposed, I think an airline should still be restricted and NOT be able to impose a surcharge.
brianne(460): In an extreme situation like the one you proposed, I think an airline should still be restricted and NOT be able to impose a surcharge.
Annot: In an extreme situation like the one you proposed, I think an airline should still be restricted and NOT be able to impose a surcharge.
I also agree that "Once you pay for it... no more money can be collected from the customer", in in extreme situations such a a spike in fuel costs.
SGSimmons(462): I also agree that "Once you pay for it... no more money can be collected from the customer", in in extreme situations such a a spike in fuel costs.
Annot: I also agree that "Once you pay for it... no more money can be collected from the customer", in in extreme situations such a a spike in fuel costs.
An airline can hedge its fuel costs by signing long term agreements.
SGSimmons(462): An airline can hedge its fuel costs by signing long term agreements.
Annot: An airline can hedge its fuel costs by signing long term agreements.
I believe that Southwest has done this.
SGSimmons(462): I believe that Southwest has done this.
Annot: I believe that Southwest has done this.
You are either in business or guaranteed profit.
Fairness(964): You are either in business or guaranteed profit.
Annot: You are either in business or guaranteed profit.
You cannot have it both ways.
Fairness(964): You cannot have it both ways.
Annot: You cannot have it both ways.
Every business has its risks and good management deals with it accordingly.
Fairness(964): Every business has its risks and good management deals with it accordingly.
Annot: Every business has its risks and good management deals with it accordingly.
Passing those risks on to your customers in inappropriate.
Fairness(964): Passing those risks on to your customers in inappropriate.

On the other hand, if customers are provided the right to cancel according to their selfdetermined "drastic"  circumstances with a full and immediate refund I might think differently.

This whole process of additional regulation is brought about because of lack of disclosure by airlines and agents when they unbundle services and initiate obscene fees for them so that we buy tickets and still don't have a deal because we may still be hit by additional fees at checkin. A DEAL SHOULD BE A DEAL!
